# MSSQL Enumeration - sysusers Table

## Objective

The goal of this task was to:

* Connect to a remote MSSQL instance
* Enumerate available databases
* Explore the sysusers table within the master database
* Identify the first user listed

---

## Target Information

* Target IP: 192.168.233.18
* Username: Administrator
* Password: (provided in lab)

---

## Connecting to MSSQL

Used Impacket MSSQL client from Kali Linux:

impacket-mssqlclient Administrator@192.168.233.18 -windows-auth

### Explanation

* impacket-mssqlclient → tool to interact with MSSQL servers
* Administrator → username
* 192.168.233.18 → target IP
* -windows-auth → use Windows authentication

After authentication, access to the SQL shell was obtained.

---

## Enumerating Databases

Executed:

SELECT name FROM sys.databases;

### Explanation

* SELECT → retrieves data
* name → column containing database names
* sys.databases → system table storing database information

This lists all available databases on the server.

---

## Switching Database Context

Ensured working within the master database:

USE master;
GO

### Explanation

* USE master → switches to the master database
* GO → executes the command batch

---

## Enumerating sysusers Table

Executed:

SELECT * FROM sysusers;

### Explanation

* SELECT * → retrieves all columns
* FROM sysusers → queries system table containing database users

---

## Analyzing Results

The output contains multiple entries with fields such as:

* uid → user ID
* name → username or role

Typical entries include:

* public
* dbo
* guest
* INFORMATION_SCHEMA
* sys

---

## Identifying the First User

The first entry in the name column was:

public

---

## Key Commands Summary

impacket-mssqlclient Administrator@192.168.233.18 -windows-auth
SELECT name FROM sys.databases;
USE master;
GO
SELECT * FROM sysusers;

---

## Additional Enumeration Commands

* SELECT @@version; → displays SQL Server version
* SELECT * FROM sys.syslogins; → lists server logins
* SELECT SYSTEM_USER; → shows current user

---

## Key Concept

The sysusers table is a built-in MSSQL system table that stores:

* Database users
* Roles
* Permission-related information

Default entries such as public and dbo are commonly present in most MSSQL environments.

---

## Result

First user in sysusers table:
public
